# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: jewel-ens
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:jewel-ens/1922-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1922 throughout the world.
[src:jewel-ens/1922-in-baseball] All Negro leagues standings below are per MLB and Seamheads.
[src:jewel-ens/1922-in-baseball] This was the third of twelve seasons of the first Negro National League.
[src:jewel-ens/1922-in-baseball] Generally, teams did not play a uniform number of games (since some teams barnstormed against other Negro baseball teams).
[src:jewel-ens/1922-in-baseball] This sometimes created a difference in who would generally be considered first place in certain years.
[src:jewel-ens/1922-in-baseball] Playoffs would not be held to determine a winner until 1925 (for which it would be used five times until 1930).
[src:jewel-ens/1922-in-baseball] For example, Indianapolis played the most games with 85, followed by Kansas City at 80, Detroit with 75, and Chicago with 62.
[src:jewel-ens/1922-in-baseball] The latter team with its superior winning percentage among the group is generally considered the pennant winner.
[src:jewel-ens/1922-in-baseball] A loose confederation of teams were gathered in the East to compete with the West, however East teams did not organize a formal league as the West did.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The **1925 Pittsburgh Pirates** finished first in the National League with a record of 95–58.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season] They defeated the Washington Senators four games to three to win their second World Series championship.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The Pirates had three future Hall of Famers in their starting lineup: Max Carey, Kiki Cuyler, and Pie Traynor.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Pittsburgh defeated the Brooklyn Robins, 21–5, on June 20 and two days later won 24–6 against the St.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Louis Cardinals, becoming the first team since 1901 to score 20 or more runs in consecutive games.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season] This feat was later matched by the 1950 Boston Red Sox.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season] October 10, 1925, at Griffith Stadium in Washington, D.C.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season] October 11, 1925, at Griffith Stadium in Washington, D.C.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-pittsburgh-pirates-season] October 12, 1925, at Griffith Stadium in Washington, D.C.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] The **1925 World Series** was the championship series of the 1925 Major League Baseball season.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] The 22nd edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff, played between the National League (NL) champion Pittsburgh Pirates and the American League (AL) champion Washington Senators, the defending World Series champion.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] The Pirates defeated the defending champion Senators in seven games to win the series, becoming the first team in North American sports history to overcome a 3–1 series deficit to win a playoff series.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] In a reversal of fortune on all counts from the previous 1924 World Series, when Washington's Walter Johnson had come back from two losses to win the seventh and deciding game, Johnson dominated in Games 1 and 4, but lost Game 7.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] The Senators built up a 3–1 Series lead.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] After Pittsburgh won the next two games, Johnson again took the mound for Game 7, and carried a 6–4 lead into the bottom of the seventh inning.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] But errors by shortstop Roger Peckinpaugh in both the seventh and eighth innings led to four unearned runs, and the Pirates become the first team in a best-of-seven Series to overcome a 3–1 Series deficit to win the championship.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] Peckinpaugh, the Senators' regular shortstop and the 1925 American League Most Valuable Player, had a tough Series in the field, committing a record eight errors.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] In the next day's *The New York Times*, James Harrison wrote "In a grave of mud was buried Walter Johnson's ambition to join the select panel of pitchers who have won three victories in one World Series.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] Twice in Game 7 the visiting Senators held leads of at least three runs over the Pirates but failed to hold them.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] In fact, after the top of the first inning, Washington led 4–0.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] Nevertheless, Pittsburgh eventually won the game, scoring three runs in the bottom of the eighth inning to turn a 6–7 deficit into a 9–7 lead.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] To date, the four-run deficit is the largest ever overcome in the seventh game of the World Series.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] It was the largest comeback in a World Series clinching game until 2024.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] A memorable play occurred during the eighth inning of Game 3.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] The Senators' Sam Rice ran after an Earl Smith line drive hit into right center field.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] Rice made a diving "catch" into the temporary stands, but did not emerge with the ball for approximately 15 seconds.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] The Pirates contested the play, saying a fan probably stuffed the ball into Rice's glove.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] The call stood and Rice parried questions about the incident for the rest of his life—never explicitly saying whether he had or had not really made the catch.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] His typical answer (including to Commissioner Landis, who said it was a good answer) was always "The umpire said I caught it." Rice left a sealed letter at the Hall of Fame to be opened after his death.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] This was Walter Johnson's second and final World Series appearance.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] By the time the original Washington Senators next reached the Fall Classic in 1933 – their last before they became the Minnesota Twins, and the city's last until the 2019 Nationals – Johnson had retired.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] This game remains to date the last road World Series game the Washington Senators/Minnesota Twins franchise has won.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] Walter Johnson pitched a complete game and allowed only five hits and struck out ten.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] The Senators got on the board in the second on Joe Harris's home run off Lee Meadows.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] In the fifth, they loaded the bases on three singles with no outs, but after Meadows struck out the next two batters, a two-run single by Sam Rice made it 3–0 Senators.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] Pie Traynor's leadoff home run in the bottom half gave the Pirates their only run in the game.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] The Senators added another run in the ninth off Johnny Morrison when Goose Goslin hit a leadoff single, moved to second on a sacrifice bunt and scored on Ossie Bluege's single.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] In Game 2, Joe Judge's second inning home run off Vic Aldridge gave the Senators a 1–0 lead, but the Pirates tied the game in the fourth on Glenn Wright's home run in the fourth off Stan Coveleski.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] In the eighth, Kiki Cuyler's two-run home run in the eighth following a Roger Peckinpaugh error that let Eddie Moore reached first put the Pirates up 3–1.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] In the ninth, the Senators loaded the bases with no outs on two walks and a single, but scored only once on Bobby Veach's sacrifice fly as Aldridge retired the next two batters and the Pirates tied the series heading to Washington.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] In Game 3, the Pirates struck first in the second when Pie Traynor hit a leadoff triple off Alex Ferguson and scored on Glenn Wright's sacrifice fly, but the Senators tied the game in the third off Ray Kremer when Sam Rice hit a leadoff single and scored on Joe Judge's double.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] The Pirates regained the lead in the fourth when Kiki Cuyler hit a leadoff single and scored on Clyde Barnhart's double.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] They added to their lead in the sixth on Kremer's RBI single with two on, but Goose Goslin's home run in the bottom half cut their lead back to one.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] Next inning, the Senators loaded the bases on a walk and two singles with one out before Judge's sacrifice fly tied the game, then an RBI single by Joe Harris put them up 4–3.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] A key play occurred in the eighth inning when Earl Smith's line drive into right-center field was caught by Sam Rice who fell into the temporary stands (see overview above).
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] Firpo Marberry pitched two shutout innings to close the game.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] This was Johnson's only post-season shutout.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] A three-run home run by Goose Goslin followed by a solo home run by Joe Harris off Emil Yde, who pitched just 2+1⁄3 innings, in the third inning put the Senators up 3–1 in the series.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] Yde became the first pitcher in the history of the World Series to surrender back-to-back home runs.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] The Pirates loaded the bases in the first, but failed to score.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] In the bottom half, Sam Rice hit a leadoff single and scored on Goose Goslin's double.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] In the third, after two walks, Clyde Barnhart's RBI single tied the game, then Pie Traynor's sacrifice fly put the Pirates up 2–1.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] Joe Harris's home run in the fourth tied the game.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] After a walk and single, back-to-back RBI singles by Kiki Cuyler and Clyde Barnhart in the seventh put the Pirates up 4–2 and knock Stan Coveleski out of the game.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] The Senators cut the lead to 4–3 in the bottom half when Nemo Leibold hit a leadoff double and scored on Sam Rice's single, but the Pirates got the run back in the eighth when Glenn Wright hit a leadoff double off Tom Zachary and scored on Stuffy McInnis's single.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] They added another run in the ninth on Wright's RBI single off Firpo Marberry with the run charged to Zachary.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] Vic Aldridge retired the Senators in order in the bottom half as the Pirates' 6–3 win forced a Game 6 in Pittsburgh.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] The Senators struck first on Goose Goslin's home run in the first, then added another run in the second on Roger Peckinpaugh's RBI double, but Pirates' Ray Kremer would shut them out afterward.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] In the third, with runners on second and third, Clyde Barnhart's groundout and Pie Traynor's single scored a run each to tie the game.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] Eddie Moore's fifth inning home run put the Pirates up 3–2.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] The Senators loaded the bases in the first on a single and two walks with one out.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] A walk to Joe Judge and RBI single by Ossie Bluege put them up 2–0 and knocked starter Vic Aldridge out of the game.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] Johnny Morrison came in relief, but a catcher interference call and error allowed two more runs to score.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] In the third, a leadoff single by Morrison, then RBI hits by Eddie Moore, Max Carey and Clyde Barnhart cut the Senators' lead to 4–3.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] In the fourth, Joe Harris's two-run double extended Washington's lead to 6–3.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] Back-to-back doubles by Carey and Kiki Cuyler in the fifth cut the lead to 6–4, then in the seventh, Moore reached first on an error before Carey's RBI double and Traynor's RBI triple tied the game.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] Roger Peckinpaugh's home run in the eighth off Ray Kremer put the Senators back atop 7–6, but in the bottom half, back-to-back two-out doubles by Earl Smith and Carson Bigbee tied the game.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] A walk and fielder's choice loaded the bases before Cuyler's two-run double put the Pirates atop 9–7.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] Red Oldham retired the Senators in order in the ninth to end the series.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] The Pirates hit Walter Johnson hard for 15 hits in a 9–7 comeback win in rainy, wet and muddy conditions.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] The Pirates were the first team to come back from a 3–1 deficit in a seven-game series.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] The Pirates returned to the World Series two years later in hopes of adding another championship, but were swept by the New York Yankees.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] They would not win the title again until 1960, in which they defeated the Yankees in seven games in a rematch.
[src:jewel-ens/1925-world-series] The Senators would make one more World Series in 1933, which they lost to the New York Giants in five games, which would be their last during their time in the nation’s capital, as the team would move to Minneapolis in 1961 to become the Minnesota Twins.
[src:jewel-ens/1927-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The **1927 Pittsburgh Pirates season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:jewel-ens/1927-pittsburgh-pirates-season] That year, the Pirates won the National League pennant, which was their second in three years and their last until 1960.
[src:jewel-ens/1927-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The team included five future Hall of Famers: Paul Waner, Lloyd Waner, Pie Traynor, Kiki Cuyler, and 20-year-old rookie Joe Cronin (who played just 12 games).
[src:jewel-ens/1927-pittsburgh-pirates-season] In the World Series, however, Pittsburgh was no match for the New York Yankees.
[src:jewel-ens/1927-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Paul Waner had one of his best seasons en route to being voted NL MVP.
[src:jewel-ens/1927-pittsburgh-pirates-season] His .380 batting average and 131 RBI paced the entire circuit.
[src:jewel-ens/1927-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Younger brother Lloyd and Traynor finished third and fifth in the batting race, respectively.
[src:jewel-ens/1927-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Pitcher Ray Kremer won the ERA title with a 2.47 ERA on his way to a 19–8 record.
[src:jewel-ens/1928-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1928 throughout the world.
[src:jewel-ens/1928-in-baseball] †Eastern Colored League disbanded mid-season, though teams continued playing.
[src:jewel-ens/1928-in-baseball] The League broke up midway through the season due to the breakdown of the founder (and manager of Hilldale Club) although the individual teams continued to play.
[src:jewel-ens/1928-in-baseball] This was the fourth season in which a playoff was held to determine the pennant, for which the first half leader would be matched against the second half winner.
[src:jewel-ens/1928-in-baseball] Louis won the first half while Chicago won the second half.
[src:jewel-ens/1928-in-baseball] As such, they met for a best-of-nine Championship Series.
[src:jewel-ens/1928-in-baseball] Louis would win the series in nine games to win their first pennant.
[src:jewel-ens/1928-in-baseball] A loose confederation of teams existed that were not part of either established leagues.
[src:jewel-ens/1930-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1930 throughout the world.
[src:jewel-ens/1930-in-baseball] This was the eleventh of twelve seasons of the original Negro National League.
[src:jewel-ens/1930-in-baseball] This was the sixth split-season and fifth season in which a playoff was held to determine the pennant, for which the first half leader would be matched against the second half winner.
[src:jewel-ens/1930-in-baseball] Louis won the first half while Detroit won the second half.
[src:jewel-ens/1930-in-baseball] As such, they met for a best-of-seven Championship Series.
[src:jewel-ens/1930-in-baseball] The playoff was held September 13–22 and would see St.
[src:jewel-ens/1930-in-baseball] Louis would win the series in seven games to win their second pennant, their second ever in three years.
[src:jewel-ens/1930-in-baseball] A loose confederation of teams were gathered mostly in the East to compete with the West, however East teams did not organize a formal league as the West did.
[src:jewel-ens/1930-in-baseball] By 1930, there had been no organized league for East Coast baseball in the Negro leagues (owing to the dissolution of the Eastern Colored League in 1928 and American Negro League in 1929).
[src:jewel-ens/1930-in-baseball] The remaining teams from the ANL and ECL played independent ball together, but they also played against teams from the Midwest.
[src:jewel-ens/1930-in-baseball] As such, the Homestead Grays challenged two teams from the NNL two distinct Series that were held over various stadiums and dates.
[src:jewel-ens/1930-in-baseball] Louis on April 19 and April 22 and won twice.
[src:jewel-ens/1930-in-baseball] They challenged the Detroit Stars to four games held from August 21 to August 28 (two in Akron and two in Detroit), which Homestead won three.
[src:jewel-ens/1930-in-baseball] On August 30–September 3, they challenged the Stars to five games (all in St.
[src:jewel-ens/1930-in-baseball] At any rate, the independent East teams then had an "East Coast Championship Series", which matched the Grays and the New York Lincoln Giants (in that same month, the Negro National League had their Championship Series), with ten games spread out over Pittsburgh, New York, and Philadelphia.
[src:jewel-ens/1931-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1931 throughout the world.
[src:jewel-ens/1931-in-baseball] This was the twelfth and final season of the original Negro National League.
[src:jewel-ens/1931-in-baseball] The season did not finish all games, which meant that while St.
[src:jewel-ens/1931-in-baseball] Louis was awarded the title, non-member Pittsburgh Crawford Giants disputed their status as champion.
[src:jewel-ens/jewel-ens] Ens also coached in the Majors for the Detroit Tigers (1932), Cincinnati Reds (1933; 1941) and Boston Braves (1934), and spent eight full seasons (1942–49) as manager of the Syracuse Chiefs, then the Reds' top farm system affiliate.
[src:jewel-ens/jewel-ens] During his 17-year active career (1908; 1910–25), Ens threw and batted right-handed, stood 5 feet, 10+1⁄2 inches (1.8 m) tall and weighed 165 pounds (75 kg).
[src:jewel-ens/jewel-ens] After a long career in minor league baseball as a shortstop and third baseman, the native of St.
[src:jewel-ens/jewel-ens] Louis made his National League debut with the Pirates at age 32 in 1922, appearing in a career-high 47 games played.
[src:jewel-ens/jewel-ens] For the next three seasons, he played a total of only 12 games, as he served as an aide to Hall of Fame manager Bill McKechnie.
[src:jewel-ens/jewel-ens] In 59 total big-league games and 186 at bats, Ens registered 54 hits, with eight doubles, four triples and one home run, hit off Wilbur Cooper of the Chicago Cubs on April 15, 1925, and sparking Pittsburgh to an 8–4 win.
[src:jewel-ens/jewel-ens] He drove in two of his career 24 runs batted in that day.
[src:jewel-ens/jewel-ens] Ens succeeded Donie Bush as manager of the Pirates late in the 1929 season.
[src:jewel-ens/jewel-ens] Pittsburgh was in second place, but 14+1⁄2 games behind the front-running Cubs, when the change happened.
[src:jewel-ens/jewel-ens] Under Ens, the Pirates won four out of five from the Cubs in a head-to-head series at Forbes Field, trimming three games off Chicago's lead, but they ultimately finished the season as runners-up, 10+1⁄2 games out, going 21–14 under Ens.
[src:jewel-ens/jewel-ens] During his two full seasons, 1930 and 1931, the Pirates posted 80–74 and 75–79 records, and Ens was replaced by George "Moon" Gibson for the 1932 campaign.
[src:jewel-ens/jewel-ens] In subsequent National League coaching assignments, he again assisted McKechnie in Boston and Cincinnati.
[src:jewel-ens/jewel-ens] After his coaching days, Ens enjoyed a successful, eight-year run as manager of the Syracuse Chiefs, making the International League playoffs five times and winning three (1942–43; 1947) Governors' Cup championships.
[src:jewel-ens/jewel-ens] He was still the incumbent manager and general manager of the Chiefs when he died at age 60 in Syracuse, from pneumonia, in January 1950.
[src:jewel-ens/jewel-ens] He was elected to the International League Hall of Fame the year of his death.
